    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm stuck on this circuit problem for my lab. if i have a resistor of 50 ohms and an inductor with an inductive reactance of 30 ohms in series, how do i find the total impedance? also what's the formula for the phase angle? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To find the total impedance ($Z$) when you have a resistor ($R$) and an inductor with an inductive reactance ($X_L$) in series, you use the Pythagorean theorem, which is $Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + X_L^2}$. This calculation will give you the total opposition to the current flow, which is the impedance.\n\nThe formula for the phase angle ($\\theta$) is found using the tangent function: $\\theta = \\arctan\\left(\\frac{X_L}{R}\\right)$. This angle tells you how much the voltage leads the current in this circuit.",
